<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1436,1915,2012]" lastBlockId="43.[151,1437,151,320]" lastPageId="43" lastPageNumber="44" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
The nearest parallel that we are aware of is the Asian species 
<taxonomicName box="[910,1096,1915,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Gangara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thyrsis">
<emphasis box="[910,1096,1915,1940]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Gangara thyrsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1112,1250,1915,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hesperiinae">Hesperiinae</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[1263,1419,1915,1940]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">incertae sedis</emphasis>
), which is a large, polyphagous palm feeder, described in detail by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bell, T. R." box="[892,1024,1951,1976]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="561 - 586" refId="ref33911" refString="Bell, T. R. (1925) The common butterflies of the plains of India (including those met with in the hill stations of the Bombay Presidency.). Part XXXIV. Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society, 30, 561 - 586." type="journal article" year="1925">Bell (1925)</bibRefCitation>
. It too has a caterpillar covered with white waxy powder, which forms projections (
<figureCitation box="[708,850,1987,2012]" captionStart="FIGURE 42" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1818,1840]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1308,1793]" captionTargetId="figure-261@42.[151,1436,1308,1793]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 42. Early stages of Gangara thyrsis on Cocos nucifera, Bangalore, India, 15 Nov 1992; 92/200. 1, final instar caterpillar, dorsal view, 38mm; 2, pupa, lateral view; 3, pupal shelter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4920916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4920916/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Figure 42.1</figureCitation>
). The mature caterpillar makes an unusual pupal chamber by rolling one or two palm leaflets in a spiral, forming a rigid tube (
<figureCitation box="[1034,1170,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 42" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1818,1840]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1308,1793]" captionTargetId="figure-261@42.[151,1436,1308,1793]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 42. Early stages of Gangara thyrsis on Cocos nucifera, Bangalore, India, 15 Nov 1992; 92/200. 1, final instar caterpillar, dorsal view, 38mm; 2, pupa, lateral view; 3, pupal shelter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4920916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4920916/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Figure 42.3</figureCitation>
), and within this, when disturbed, the pupa (
<figureCitation box="[379,511,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 42" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1818,1840]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1308,1793]" captionTargetId="figure-261@42.[151,1436,1308,1793]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 42. Early stages of Gangara thyrsis on Cocos nucifera, Bangalore, India, 15 Nov 1992; 92/200. 1, final instar caterpillar, dorsal view, 38mm; 2, pupa, lateral view; 3, pupal shelter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4920916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4920916/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Figure 42.2</figureCitation>
) vibrates rapidly and violently, drumming against the sides of the shelter, which is certainly a deterrent to an inexperienced predator (or indeed entomologist in MJWC’s personal experience), and may also be a behaviour to crush any intruding predator or parasitoid insect (note the heavily chitinized spurs laterally before the cremaster, discussed under 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Larsen" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[676,915,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Zophopetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerymica">
<emphasis box="[676,915,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Zophopetes cerymica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
above).
</paragraph>
